Battle Frontier Pokémon

The following Pokémon are used in the Battle Tower, Castle, Arcade, and Factory. Every individual species used by these facilities can have between one and four movesets associated with them. There are roughly four groups of 'power levels' of species that can be encountered:

  1. Low Tier: Consists largely of first-stage Pokémon and some weak evolved Pokémon. Species in this tier have one set associated with them.
  2. Mid Tier: Consists largely of middle-stage Pokémon and some weak fully evolved Pokémon. Species in this tier have two sets associated with them.
  3. High Tier: Consists largely of fully-evolved Pokémon. Species in this tier have four sets associated with them.
  4. Legendary Tier: Consists of all Legendaries that are legal in the Battle Frontier. Species in this tier have four sets associated with them.

The common way of referring to a Pokémon with multiple sets is to identify the set with a number, e.g. "Set2 Rayquaza", "Rayquaza1", or "Rayquaza-3". In some early documentation, sets may instead be referred to with the number given in the below table ("999 Rayquaza"). For my tables, I will be using the "Rayquaza-1" method of referring to sets.

The list of Pokémon used in the Battle Hall is different from the list used here. Please see the Battle Hall Pokémon page for information.

  • Low Tier
  • Mid Tier Set-1
  • Mid Tier Set-2
  • High Tier Set-1
  • High Tier Set-2
  • High Tier Set-3
  • High Tier Set-4
  • Legendary Tier

Battle Tower, Castle, and Arcade Set Mechanics

In these three facilities, any enemy Trainer the player faces, apart from the Frontier Brain, will be pulled from a pre-existing list of 300 Trainers. Each Trainer has a roster of Pokémon and an IV value associated with them, and the game will choose three random Pokémon from their roster to make the player battle. The chosen Pokémon will never be the same species or have the same held item as each other. The Trainers page gives more detail and shows each Trainer's roster.

The first 220 Trainers on the list are split into seven groups, where each group can only use one set of Pokémon from a specific tier. Trainers 221-300 have some Trainers that can use Pokémon from multiple sets, as well as Legendaries, and a few of them use some Set-2 Mid Tier Pokémon as well.

The number of battles the player has participated in will determine which Trainers can be selected as enemies, and therefore, which sets of Pokémon the player might face. The progression proceeds as follows:

  • Battles 1-6: Low Tier, 3IV
  • Battle 7: Set-1 Mid Tier, 6IV
  • Battles 8-13: Low Tier, 3IV or Set-1 Mid Tier, 6IV
  • Battle 14: Set-2 Mid Tier, 9IV
  • Battles 15-20: Set-1, 6IV or Set-2, 9IV Mid Tier
  • Battle 21: Set-1 High Tier, 12IV
  • Battles 22-27: Set-2 Mid Tier, 9IV or Set-1, 12IV High Tier
  • Battle 28: Set-2 High Tier, 15IV
  • Battles 29-34: Set-1, 12IV or Set-2, 15IV High Tier
  • Battle 35: Set-3 High Tier, 18IV
  • Battles 36-41: Set-2, 15IV or Set-3, 18IV High Tier
  • Battle 42: Set-4 High Tier, 21IV
  • Battles 43-48: Set-3, 18IV or Set-4, 21IV High Tier
  • Battle 49: Any High or Legendary Tier, with a few Set-2 Mid Tier Pokémon, 31IV
  • Battles 50+: Any High or Legendary Tier, with a few Set-2 Mid Tier Pokémon, 21IV or 31IV

Battle Factory Set Mechanics

In this facility, the same set of 300 Trainers can be chosen as enemies, but they will not use the roster associated with them. They will instead use a random set of Pokémon chosen from a specific tier, depending on the mode (Level 50 or Open Level). Their IVs are different as well. The progression is as follows.

Group IVs Level 50 Open Level
1-100 0 Low Tier Set-1 High Tier
101-120 4 Set-1 Mid Tier Set-2 High Tier
121-140 8 Set-2 Mid Tier Set-3 High Tier
141-160 12 Set-1 High Tier Set-4 High Tier
161-180 16 Set-2 High Tier Any High or Legendary Tier
181-200 20 Set-3 High Tier Any High or Legendary Tier
201-220 24 Set-4 High Tier Any High or Legendary Tier
221-300 31 Any High or Legendary Tier Any High or Legendary Tier

Thorton has some bugs associated with the sets he can choose from, detailed on the Factory page.

Additionally, the Pokémon players receive as rentable options at the start of each round of seven battles are chosen based on tiers. Until the player 'unlocks' all tiers of Pokémon, the rentable set will be chosen from a specific tier, depending on the mode (Level 50 or Open Level) and the number of battles the player has played. One or more Pokémon may be 'upgraded', meaning it will be replaced with a Pokémon from the next tier, and its IVs will increase. Whether Pokémon are upgraded depends on how many swaps the player has made; see the Battle Factory page for more info. The rentable Pokémon progression is as follows:

Battle(s) Level 50 (Regular) Level 50 (Upgraded) Open Level (Regular) Open Level (Upgraded)
1-7 Low Tier, 0IV N/A Set-1 High Tier, 0IV N/A
8-14 Set-1 Mid Tier, 4IV Set-2 Mid Tier, 8IV Set-2 High Tier, 4IV Set-3 High Tier, 8IV
15-21 Set-2 Mid Tier, 8IV Set-1 High Tier, 12IV Set-3 High Tier, 8IV Set-4 High Tier, 12IV
22-28 Set-1 High Tier, 12IV Set-2 High Tier, 16IV Set-4 High Tier, 12IV Any High or Legendary Tier, 16IV
29-35 Set-2 High Tier, 16IV Set-3 High Tier, 20IV Any High or Legendary Tier, 16IV Any High or Legendary Tier, 20IV
36-42 Set-3 High Tier, 20IV Set-4 High Tier, 24IV Any High or Legendary Tier, 20IV Any High or Legendary Tier, 24IV
43-49 Set-4 High Tier, 24IV Any High or Legendary Tier, 31IV Any High or Legendary Tier, 24IV Any High or Legendary Tier, 31IV
50+ Any High or Legendary Tier, 31IV N/A Any High or Legendary Tier, 31IV N/A

Some additional resources:

  • This page contains a damage calculator with all the movesets of Battle Frontier Pokémon pre-loaded, using the numbers for each set. Sets where the number begins with the letter 'H' are used by the Battle Hall only. Remember that you will need to update the IVs yourself in accordance with the Trainer faced.
  • This post contains some Speed values associated with enemy Pokémon with 31 IVs. This can be useful for determining what kinds of Speed benchmarks your Pokémon will need to hit to accomplish their goals.
  • The lookup tool linked in this post allows you to enter a Trainer's name and their Pokémon and get information about the possible Pokémon you might face or are facing. This currently only has data for Trainers that can be faced in battle 50 onward.
  • This spreadsheet contains many general resources about the Platinum/HeartGold/SoulSilver battle facilities in one place; you may find the spreadsheet easier to use than this webpage. This website has some corrections that, as of this writing, aren't present in the spreadsheet, such as: Miltank is listed with number 539 twice; Pokémon with neutral natures may have the incorrect nature listed; the list of Trainers is missing some data for the first 100 Trainers in the list.
